Christian Tamondong’s Effervescence presents works that may evoke a fizzing sense of elation in terms of appearance, despite a closer look suggesting otherwise. From the crevices of these vibrant distractions may arise a broader sense of emotions, including disdain, contempt, sorrow.

These pieces pose one question: Do we really know what we think we know?

Kobusher’s Twelve carry on the artist’s mission to mess with our established identification of pop culture icons. Characters we have come to know and love get twisted and smashed and turned inward just before the point of unrecognition.

These pieces pose one question: Do we really know what we think we know?

"I am intrigued with the shapes people choose as their symbols to create a language. There is within all forms a basic structure, an indication of the entire object with a minimum of lines that becomes a symbol. This is common to all languages, all people, all times." - Keith Haring, journal entry, 1979

Christian Tamondong’s Effervescence presents works that may evoke a fizzing sense of elation in terms of appearance, despite a closer look suggesting otherwise. From the crevices of these vibrant distractions may arise a broader sense of emotions, including disdain, contempt, sorrow.

These pieces by the artist pose one question: Do we really know what we think we know?
